VThe old story about climate protection is that it's costly,
p4
aVor it would have been done already.
p5
aVSo government needs to make us do something painful to fix it.
p6
aVThe new story about climate protection
p7
aVis that it's not costly, but profitable.
p8
aVThis was a simple sign error,
p9
aVbecause it's cheaper to save fuel than to buy fuel,
p10
aVas is well known to companies that do it all the time \u2014
p11
aVfor example, Dupont, SD micro electronics.
p12
aVMany other firms \u2014 IBM \u2014 are reducing their energy intensity
p13
aVroutinely six percent a year by fixing up their plants,
p14
aVand they get their money back in two or three years.
p15
aVThat's called a profit.
p16
aa(lp17
VNow, similarly, the old story about oil is that if we wanted to save very much of it,
p18
aVit would be expensive, or we would have done it already,
p19
aVbecause markets are essentially perfect.
p20
aVIf, of course, that were true, there would be no innovation,
p21
aVand nobody could make any money.
p22
aVBut the new story about oil
p23
aVis the government doesn't have to force us to do painful things to get off oil \u2014
p24
aVnot just incrementally, but completely \u2014
p25
aVquite the contrary. The United States, for example,
p26
aVcan completely eliminate its use of oil
p27
aVand rejuvenate the economy at the same time,
p28
aVled by business for profit,
p29
aVbecause it's so much cheaper to save and substitute for the oil
p30
aVthan to keep on buying it.
p31
aVThis process will also be catalyzed by the military
p32
aVfor its own reasons of combat effectiveness and preventing conflict,
p33
aVparticularly over oil.
p34
aa(lp35
VThis thesis is set out in a book called "Winning the Oil Endgame"
p36
aVthat four colleagues and I wrote
p37
aVand have posted for free at Oilendgame.com \u2014
p38
aVabout 170,000 downloads so far.
p39
aVAnd it was co-sponsored by the Pentagon \u2014
p40
aVit's independent, it's peer-reviewed
p41
